07023nam a22010455i 9783110679847DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106798477 a10.1515/97831106798472doi  a(DE-B1597)537211  a(OCoLC)1196260069  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041902bisacsh0486pa100qDE-10100aRevisiting Aristotle’s Fragments :bNew Essays on the Fragments of Aristotle’s Lost Works /ced. by António Pedro Mesquita, Simon Noriega-Olmos, Christopher John Ignatius Shields. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (VI, 304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeiträge zur Altertumskunde ,x1616-0452 ;v38800tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tI. Philosophy and Philosophical Perspectives in Aristotle’s Fragments -- tWhat is Philosophy in the Protrepticus? -- tAristotle’s Philosophêmata -- tOn the Role of the Platonic Interlocutor in Aristotle’s Dialogue On Philosophy -- tAristotle on Wine and Intoxication -- tII. Philosophical Problems in Light of Aristotle’s Fragments -- tThe Lost On Philosophy and Aristotle’s Natural Philosophy -- tAthenaeus’ Deipnosophistae 7 and Aristotle’s Lost Zoïka or On Fish -- tIn Dialogue about Harmony -- tThe Spurious Fragments of a Supposed Aristotelian Argument from Design -- tAristotle’s Lost Dialogue On Good Birth and Kingship as the Best Regime -- tDid Homer Nod Off? Aristotle and Homeric Problem-Solving -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Passages -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe philosophical and philological study of Aristotle fragments and lost works has fallen somewhat into the background since the 1960’s. This is regrettable considering the different and innovative directions the study of Aristotle has taken in the last decades. This collection of new peer-reviewed essays applies the latest developments and trends of analysis, criticism, and methodology to the study of Aristotle’s fragments. The individual essays use the fragments as tools of interpretation, shed new light on different areas of Aristotle philosophy, and lay bridges between Aristotle’s lost and extant works. The first part shows how Aristotle frames parts of his own understanding of Philosophy in his published, 'popular' work. The second part deals with issues of philosophical interpretation in Aristotle’s extant works which can be illuminated by fragments of his lost works. The philosophical issues treated in this section range from Theology to Natural Science, Psychology, Politics, and Poetics. As a whole, the book articulates a new approach to Aristotle’s lost works, by providing a reassessment and new methodological explorations of the fragments.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aAristoteles. 4aAristotelische Tradition. 4aFragment. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAristotelian tradition.  aAristotle's fragments.  aAristotle's lost works.  aAristotle.1 aFalcon, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHildebrandt, Ronja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayhew, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMegino, Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMesquita, António Pedro, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoore, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoriega-Olmos, Simon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPedro Mesquita, António, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetrova,